{
  "slug": "the-sinners-surge-plus-the-val-kilmer-hall-of-fame",
  "title": "The 'Sinners' Surge. Plus: The Val Kilmer Hall of Fame!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Chris Ryan"
  ],
  "published": "2025-04-23",
  "runtimeMin": 96,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Chris Ryan open on the 'Weapons' teaser, then spend the first half on Ryan Coogler's 'Sinners': the one-crazy-night structure, genre as vocabulary, a vampire framework with no crosses, and the box-office noise around Coogler's 25-year ownership deal. Then they build a ten-film Val Kilmer Hall of Fame after his death at 65, grading his whole filmography green, yellow, or red. Tombstone, Heat, and The Doors are the three to start with; Spartan sneaks in, MacGruber and The Saint don't.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Trailer talk: 'Weapons'",
      "note": "the teaser drop",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Weapons",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Zach Cregger's 'Barbarian' follow-up, bumped up to an August release and pitched (a framework they expect to regret) as 'Magnolia, but horror.' The hosts loved the 45-second teaser (a town's kids running off into the night, arms outstretched) and its Longlegs-style viral marketing, a late-'90s GeoCities-style maybrookmissing.com site. Josh Brolin and Julia Garner star; Brolin's role was reportedly once meant for Pedro Pascal."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The 'Sinners' surge",
      "note": "Chris Ryan's takeaways, plus the box-office discourse",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Sinners",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Ryan Coogler's original vampire movie, with Michael B. Jordan in a double role as Smoke and Stack. Chris Ryan came out loving it: a great one-crazy-night movie whose compression films do better than TV, a filmmaker using genre as vocabulary the way Godard and Leone did, and a post-Judeo-Christian vampire framework with no crosses or holy water. Jack O'Connell's Remmick reads as a 'white ally' turned bad, drawing people into a hive mind. The piercing-the-veil sequence and Brittany Howard's 'Pale, Pale Moon' are the peaks. Framed as a possible genre-movie Best Picture play, like Dune: Part Two or Everything Everywhere. Much of the segment is the box-office argument: profitability, streaming and licensing tails, and Coogler's much-discussed 25-year copyright reversion."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "halloffame",
      "heading": "The Val Kilmer Hall of Fame",
      "honoree": "Val Kilmer",
      "note": "the ten inducted films, after grading his whole filmography green, yellow, or red",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Real Genius",
          "year": 1985,
          "role": "Chris Knight",
          "note": "Green on the first ballot. Chris Ryan's touchstone: the comic timing that could have made Kilmer a Bill Murray or a Cruise, the 'it's a moral imperative' bit, a total cable classic. Martha Coolidge directs."
        },
        {
          "title": "Top Gun",
          "year": 1986,
          "role": "Tom 'Iceman' Kazansky",
          "note": "Going in as Iceman. He goes toe-to-toe with Cruise in the locker-room and volleyball scenes before the last act hamstrings the character. The two were neck-and-neck for stardom for a while."
        },
        {
          "title": "Willow",
          "year": 1988,
          "role": "Madmartigan",
          "note": "Yellowed, then promoted to green. Ron Howard's fantasy, a partner piece to The Princess Bride; Madmartigan is a Han Solo-ish goofball trapped in King Arthur's body. Sean saw it in a theater at six and it was his shit."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Doors",
          "year": 1991,
          "role": "Jim Morrison",
          "note": "He literally becomes Morrison: the band said the recordings sounded better than Jim. A wildly flawed movie, but eerie when Val's locked in during the performance scenes. One of three films they'd hand a newcomer."
        },
        {
          "title": "Tombstone",
          "year": 1993,
          "role": "Doc Holliday",
          "note": "Sean's favorite Kilmer performance. Only five or so scenes, but 'I'm your huckleberry,' the gun-flipping showdown, and the Johnny Ringo standoff. Both agree it's weird he wasn't nominated."
        },
        {
          "title": "Batman Forever",
          "year": 1995,
          "role": "Bruce Wayne / Batman",
          "note": "In as an artifact, not a performance: he played Batman, the first line of the obituary, one of seven men to do it on film. Not a referendum on the movie."
        },
        {
          "title": "Heat",
          "year": 1995,
          "role": "Chris Shiherlis",
          "note": "'The deepest, darkest green we've ever had.' Possessed opposite Pacino and De Niro with barely any dialogue; the no-go-sign scene at the end. The best part of the never-made Heat 2."
        },
        {
          "title": "Spartan",
          "year": 2004,
          "role": "Robert Scott",
          "note": "Sean's one granted pick, and he knows it's divisive. Kilmer sings David Mamet's dialogue ('set that motherfucker to receive') even though the two reportedly clashed, which may be exactly why the performance crackles."
        },
        {
          "title": "Kiss Kiss Bang Bang",
          "year": 2005,
          "role": "Gay Perry",
          "note": "Green with a bullet. His affinity for Shane Black's tone, maybe the funniest performance of his late career, in RDJ's comeback. Makes you wish he'd been in The Nice Guys."
        },
        {
          "title": "Top Gun: Maverick",
          "year": 2022,
          "role": "Tom 'Iceman' Kazansky",
          "note": "The capstone, made after the tracheotomies and the voice box. One near-wordless scene with Cruise that lands hard. Sean hears Amanda's voice threatening assassination if it were left off."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
